

<html>
<head>
<title>Statistical Inference II Classnote</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=right><font size=-2>[Stat Inf II
classnotes, ISI, Kolkata]
</td></tr></table>
<h1>Two sample inference</h1>




<h3>Rank statistics</h3>

So far we have seen a number of two sample tests. These as well as many
others all use test statistics of a general form called <i>linear rank
statistics</i>. We discuss this below.
<p>
Our set up is as before:


<blockquote>
X<sub>1</sub>,...,X<sub>m</sub> iid F<br>
Y<sub>1</sub>,...,Y<sub>n</sub> iid G<br>
X's and Y's are mutually independent<br>
F, G both continuous and unknown.
</blockquote>

<p>
Pool the samples together as

<blockquote>
X<sub>1</sub>,...,X<sub>m</sub>,Y<sub>1</sub>,...,Y<sub>n</sub>
</blockquote>

Let the rank vector of the pooled data be

<blockquote>
R<sub>1</sub>,...,R<sub>m</sub>,R<sub>m+1</sub>,...,
R<sub>m+n</sub>
</blockquote>

Thus, 

<blockquote>
R<sub>i</sub> = rank of X<sub>i</sub> in the pooled data for 1

<img src=
"resources/statinf2/leq.png"
align=top>

 i 
   <img src=
   "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
   align=top>
   
    m
</blockquote>

and

<blockquote>
R<sub>m+j</sub> = rank of Y<sub>j</sub> in the pooled data for 1

<img src=
"resources/statinf2/leq.png"
align=top>

 j 
   <img src=
   "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
   align=top>
   
    n.
</blockquote>

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#995555"></td>
   <td>
   <b>Example:</b> 
   
   In a controlled experiment to measure the effectiveness of a treatment
   suppose that the control group yields the following measurements:
   
   <blockquote>
   X<sub>1</sub> = 2, X<sub>2</sub> = 4, X<sub>3</sub> = 9,
   </blockquote>
   
   and the treatment group produces
   
   <blockquote>
   Y<sub>1</sub> = 5, Y<sub>2</sub> = 8.
   </blockquote>
   
   Then here are the pooled data and the rank vector:
   
   <blockquote>
   <pre>
   pooled data: 2  4  9  5  8
   rank vector: 1  2  5  3  4
   </pre>
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td bgcolor="#cccccc">
   <b>Definition:</b>
   
   A statistic that is a function of the rank vector is called a <i>rank
   statistic</i>. 
   
   </td></tr></table>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td bgcolor="#cccccc">
   <b>Definition:</b>
   
   Let A be any known (m+n) by (m+n) matrix with (i,j)-th element denoted by
   a(i,j). The 
   
   <blockquote>
   
   <img src=
   "resources/statinf2/sum.gif"
   align=middle>
   
   a(i,R<sub>i</sub>)
   </blockquote>
   
   is called a <i>linear</i> rank statistic.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   
How to check that a given rank statistic is indeed a linear rank
statistic? The following theorem helps you to do this.
<p>

<table><tr><td bgcolor="#cccccc">
<b>Theorem:</b>

Suppose that T(<u>R</u>) is a rank statistics, where <u>R</u> denotes the
rank vector, ie, permutations of 1,...,N, say. 
Let <u>S</u> be any rank vector, and i,j be in {1,...,N}. 
Define <u>S(i,j)</u> as the permutation obtained from <u>S</u> by swapping
i and j. Then T is a linear rank statistic iff 

<blockquote>
T(<u>S</u>)-T(<u>S(i,j)</u>) is free of S<sub>k</sub> for all
k 
  <img src=
  "resources/statinf2/neq.png"
  align=top>
  
   i,j.
</blockquote>


</td></tr></table>

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=1 bgcolor="#cccccc"></td>
   <td>
   <b><i>Proof:</i></b> 
   Direct argument.
   <img src="resources/statinf2/square.gif">
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise RANK.1:</font></b> 
   
   Is the Mann-Whitney U-statistic a rank statistic? Is it linear? If so, find A.
   <br><i>[Hint: Explicitly write down
    the U-statistic in terms of the ranks.]</i>
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise RANK.2:</font></b> 
   
   Do the same for the 2-stample KS test statistic, D<sub>+</sub>
   <br>
       <i>[Hint:
       
       Use the theorem above.
       ]
       </i>
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise RANK.3:</font></b> 
   
   Do the same for the Wald-Wolfowitz run test.
   <br>
       <i>[Hint:
       
       Use the theorem above.
       ]
       </i>
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td bgcolor="#cccccc">
   <b>Definition:</b>
   
   A statistic of the form 
   
   <blockquote>
   
   <img src=
   "resources/statinf2/sum.gif"
   align=middle>
   
    c<sub>i</sub> a(R<sub>i</sub>)
   </blockquote>
   
   is called a <i>simple, linear rank statistic</i>, where c<sub>i</sub>'s
   are any constants and a(.) is any function.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise RANK.4:</font></b> 
   
   To justify the terminology used we need to show that a simple linear rank
   statistic is indeed a linear rank statistic as we have defined earlier. In
   particular, show that a simple linear rank statistic corresponds to a A
   matrix of the form 
   
   <blockquote>
   A = u v' 
   </blockquote>
   
   where u and v are column vectors.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<h4>Computing moments of simple linear rank statistics</h4>

Let
 
 <blockquote>
 S = 
     <img src=
     "resources/statinf2/sum.gif"
     align=middle>
     
      c<sub>i</sub> a(R<sub>i</sub>)
 </blockquote>
 
We shall compute E(S) and Var(S) under H<sub>0</sub>: F = G. 
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise RANK.5:</font></b> 
   
   Show that under H<sub>0</sub>, 
   
   <blockquote>
   each R<sub>i</sub> ~ discrete uniform {1,...,m+n}
   </blockquote>
   
   and 
   
   <blockquote>
   (R<sub>1</sub>,...,R<sub>m+n)</sub>) ~ discrete uniform over all
   (m+n)! possible permutations of {1,...,m+n}
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise RANK.6:</font></b> 
   
   Use the last exercise to show that
   
   <blockquote>
   E(S) = (m+n)cbar * abar
   </blockquote>
   
   where cbar and abar of averages of c<sub>i</sub>'s and a(i)'s respectively.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise RANK.7:</font></b> 
   
   Show that
   
   <blockquote>
   cov(a(R<sub>i</sub>),a(R<sub>j</sub>))= 
   -&sigma;<sup>2</sup><sub>a</sub>/(m+n)
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise RANK.8:</font></b> 
   
   Show that 
   
   <blockquote>
   Var(S) = (m+n-1) &sigma;<sup>2</sup><sub>a</sub>
   &sigma;<sup>2</sup><sub>c</sub>,
   </blockquote>
   
   where  &sigma;<sup>2</sup><sub>c</sub> is the variance of the
   c<sub>i</sub>'s. The denominator in &sigma;<sup>2</sup><sub>c</sub> is 
   (m+n-1).
   Similarly for &sigma;<sup>2</sup><sub>a</sub>.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   


